This was certainly not my mother's detergent. With the pods, here I was, spraying the clothes with zout first, getting feisty with extra oxy clean... Nope. Ghost spots of grease and dirt, still there. Oh, and there's the pod ghost. I have an HE front loader. I can't necessarily check the thing and make sure it dissolved at the right time. So, of course, I passed the stuff on to a friend, that she may partake in my mother's hard-eared wisdom.  Thus, in my humble opinion, buy the stuff, get over it and don't throw it away! AUTHOR: Jim gearhead4
TITLE: No spills laundry detergent for any washing machine

content_cleaned: These handy Tide Pods eliminate the need to measure out detergent and fabric softener, combining all the steps in a simple liquid packet about the size of a large gumball. This gets added to the drum of the washing machine prior to the laundry and then the laundry goes in after it. Sweet and simple. After using these pods on my laundry I'm perfectly happy with their overall cleaning power and it is admittedly easy to have everything combined in one small package rather than measuring out liquids into the dispenser. While I didn't notice a difference in my laundry from it's usual washing, there also was no soap residue left, and nothing that irritated my family's sensitive skin, so I'm pleased and perfectly happy to use them. A few issues however. The first is these Pods are one size fits all. They are only designed for side loading washers and, if you're not doing a full load of laundry, you can't cut down the amount of the Pod to match. The Pods themselves are very soft, and while I didn't try to puncture one to see how difficult that would be, there is an obvious risk of the Pod breaking before it reaches the washer. If you have a laundry room in your home and can keep your detergent within easy reach--no problem. The plastic bag the Pods come in is sturdy enough to keep them safe. But if, like me, you share a washer with others, or go to the local laundromat, it's not going to really be much more convenient than carrying a container of detergent to carry the whole bag. My biggest concern is for parents. Having two young children myself, I am always aware of potential hazards and things that need to be kept out of reach. Obviously, laundry detergent always should be out of little one's hands. But the Pods themselves look like some kind of colorful candy or toy. The colorful swirls of stainlifter and fabric softener on the on side may look snazzy for packaging, but they also make these look appealing to kiddies. I'm not saying parents will necessarily let them fall into the hands of children, but it's still a danger. In conclusion, these are good if convenience is your goal and you can store these close to your washer to use. But I'll stick to regular detergent so I can vary the amount I use. Happy Washing! Shanshad. ^_^

AUTHOR: B. Anderson
TITLE: Keeps my laundry room clean!

content_cleaned: I decided to give the Tide Pods a try since I used to use nothing but Tide liquid detergent and these new pods promised to be as easy as the Cascade Complete All-in-1 packets I've been using for several years. For starters, I use a Kenmore High-Efficiency Top-Load washer. The instructions for my washer clearly state that the detergent goes in before the clothes, so I just drop in one of these Tide Pods before I put in the laundry. The Pods feel slimy in my hands (unlike Cascade Complete dishwasher packets which feel like plastic) but you just grab one and toss it into your washer machine rather than measuring out detergent.  The Pods have always dissolved completely in the wash when I have used them but I'm not sure how well they would dissolve if you forgot and just tossed one in on top of your laundry. I suspect those reviewers reporting the Tide Pods do not completely dissolve might not be putting the Pods in before the laundry.  The scent is essentially the same as the Tide liquid detergent I used to use, but my wife switched to a Melaleuca brand detergent a few weeks before I started testing the Tide Pods and the Tide detergent has a MUCH stronger fragrance than the Melaleuca detergent. In any case, it smells clean and isn't off-putting.  I have just used a single Pod in every washer load ... even large loads that might technically be considered overloading my washer. My clothes have been coming out perfectly clean. The package says to use two Pods with heavily soiled loads but I haven't tried that yet. That is the one negative issue with using the Pods: no ability to measure partial loads of detergent.  If you are washing a small load then you don't need an entire Pod but you have to use an entire Pod anyway. Likewise, if you're washing a large load or a slightly dirtier load then you might want to use a little extra detergent but not twice the amount used for a regular load. If you use the Pods you have to use one or two ... you can't break them in half.  Overall, I like the convenience of using the Tide Pods with my laundry and I would recommend these since they make laundry a little quicker. I just wish Tide made these so you can break each Pod in half ... that way you can use a half a Pod for a small load of laundry or use one and a half Pods for a larger/dirtier load.

AUTHOR: David Nox
TITLE: Pods Worked well but they were not for me

content_cleaned:
Laundry detergent is one of the few products where I won't buy the store brand. I have teenaged athlete sons and their clothes are disgusting; I have found over the years that only Tide and Wisk get their clothes really clean (I buy whichever is on sale that day). So I am already a Tide-user. I had been eyeing these up in the store, assuming they were more expensive and wondering if they'd be worth it, so I was happy to get these. If you use dishwasher 'pacs' then you get the idea.... this is detergent inside a little plastic pod (that dissolves in the cycle). You throw it in (before the clothes!) instead of measuring and pouring in the detergent. Easy Peasy, and it's Tide so it works. These pods got the clothes just as clean as traditional Tide. And frankly, I enjoy a product that saves even a few seconds per laundry load. The downside is (surprisingly) not the price, but the fact that you can't use less detergent for a smaller load. THE GOOD:
+ Tide works well; the pods are no different
+ Easy to throw in, and no gloppy (or powdery) mess like with traditional detergent.

THE PRICE:
*Surprisingly, not that much more expensive than regular liquid Tide. These 40 pods sell for $11.57.... which is about 30 cents per load. 50 oz of Liquid Tide, advertised as enough for 32 loads, sells (here on amazon) for $7.99... or 25 cents per load.

THE BAD:
- Well, obviously, you can't adjust the amount of detergent for your load. I almost always use less detergent than directed anyway, and I definitely use less for small loads, or my own clothes. This of course means that I get MORE loads per bottle than advertised, making the price difference between liquid and pods more significant.

BOTTOM LINE: Saves time, effort, and mess while costing only slightly more - great! But you can't adjust depending on your load, making the cost per load, in essence, more.

AUTHOR: Leif Sheppard
TITLE: Tide Detergent Pods

content_cleaned:
Great product and very easy to use. I love it. I wish Amazon would maintain stock as these pods are very expensive in my rural area. If the clothes are very dirty, use 2 pods. I've not had a single unsatisfactory load.

Now, let's address this issue of the pods failing to dissolve. I have well water which is very hard and it comes out of the ground very, very cold at around 40 degrees F. Hard water and very cold temperatures ought to be the perfect situation for the a gummy dissolve failure. But it doesn't happen.

Why? The directions clearly state to put the pod in the machine before adding the clothes. The water plus the pounding of the clothes will certainly break these things down. If added after the clothes, I could see the undissolved pod easily 'floating' toward the drain where it would not be subjected to the pounding necessary to break up.

Added first, it is virtually impossible for these pods not to break down.

One note of caution. Front loaders have a "clean" cycle used to clean the drums. You must run that cycle, with no clothes and no soap at least once a month. This will clean your machine of soap residue. Running this cycle will amaze you at the soap build up and the water and steam will be very, very foamy. This cycle improves the efficiency of your machine too.

content_cleaned: I'm going to preface this by saying that I'm a big fan of original Tide. Nothing gets clothes quite as clean and fresh-smelling (from my experience) and it's from that perspective that I was looking forward to trying Tide detergent Pods.  The Tide Detergent Pods basically take a no-nonsense, convenient approach to doing laundry. If it's a standard load, you toss one pod into the washer before throwing the laundry in. If it's going to be a large or heavily-soiled load, then toss in a second Pod. That's simple enough. The outer pod dissolves, releasing the detergent, stain fighters and brighteners into the wash. I've washed 12 loads with the Pods so far, from dark clothing, to linens to towels, and everything comes out clean and fresh-smelling. At first I thought the little Pod might not be up to that task, but it does the job admirably.  The thing is, I don't really get why one would go with the Pods over standard Tide. I know convenience is the primary thing they're going for here, but is it really that inconvenient to pour a capful of liquid or scoop some Tide powder? The short answer to that is no, and I honestly prefer the flexibility of being able to add or subtract just enough detergent to get the job done. With the Pods, you basically have to toss another in, which as far as cost goes, is like having to put two scoops into a load when you just need a little more. I can see these being handy if you're going to have to do some laundry on the go, but Tide seems to be positioning these as a replacement to their other products. I can't speak for anyone else, but that's not happening in my house.  Tide Pods are a decent product. They're not overly expensive and they definitely do what they're supposed to do (get clothes clean and fresh). That said, outside of some very specific circumstances, I just don't see why you'd stop using traditional detergents and go with the Pod exclusively.

AUTHOR: Kaos
TITLE: Warning from loyal Tide user

content_cleaned: We've used the all in one Purex laundry sheets and the Purex UltraPacks, so we looked forward to using Tide's new Pods. These are soft, squishy packets sealed in polyvinyl that dissolves in the wash. I've never felt breast implants, but I imagine they'd feel a little like a Tide Pod. When Mrs. Spudman saw me squeezing a couple Pods, I explained it was for experimental purposes only.  The Pods are small and condensed with 90% active ingredients separated into three compartments, ingredients that clean, whiten, and fight stains. Water is the number one ingredient in Tide Liquid Free in which it is labeled a process aid. Linear alkylbenzene sulfonates, a surfacant, is the number one ingredient in Tide Pods, followed by C12-16 Pareth-9 and a host of other ingredients only a chemist would love or understand. Water is the fifth ingredient in Tide Pods and in the Pods is called a solvent.  Upon opening the package containing all of those Spring Meadow gel packs, one's olfactory senses are overwhelmed by the intense aroma. It's not unpleasant at all, but anyone sensitive to strong scents might prefer the Purex Free and Clear Ultra Packs.  DIRECTIONS: Add pack to drum. Add clothes. That's it. No measuring. No fuss.  FINALLY: There's no doubt that Tide Pods are oozing with convenience and are easy to use. There's also no large plastic bottle to dispose of afterwards. I think these would be great to take on vacation, but packed carefully because a punctured Pod would be a messy Pod. On our last vacation we used the Purex all in one sheets with great success.  Tide touts the time saving feature of these Pods, but we're not impressed by the few seconds of time saved. However, anyone who struggles with heavy laundry containers will welcome the ease of dropping in a Pod.  LIMITATIONS: This is a one size fits all product. Just drop in one pod unless you're doing a very large or a very dirty load. If you want to pretreat or add more brightener, you'll need to supplement with another product or products.  PERFORMANCE: Tide is usually ranked at or near the top of the list by the well known consumer magazine. Purex is usually rated much lower. In our informal testing in Spudman Laboratories,though, we noticed little difference in brightness or stain fighting ability between the two brands. For us the slight improvement in performance may not be worth the extra cost of the Tide product.

AUTHOR: Wandering Hoosier "dog lover"
TITLE: Great Little Pods

content_cleaned: These handy Tide Pods eliminate the need to measure out detergent and fabric softener, combining all the steps in a simple liquid packet about the size of a large gumball. This gets added to the drum of the washing machine prior to the laundry and then the laundry goes in after it. Sweet and simple.  After using these pods on my laundry I'm perfectly happy with their overall cleaning power and it is admittedly easy to have everything combined in one small package rather than measuring out liquids into the dispenser. While I didn't notice a difference in my laundry from it's usual washing, there also was no soap residue left, and nothing that irritated my family's sensitive skin, so I'm pleased and perfectly happy to use them.  A few issues however. The first is these Pods are one size fits all. They are only designed for side loading washers and, if you're not doing a full load of laundry, you can't cut down the amount of the Pod to match. The Pods themselves are very soft, and while I didn't try to puncture one to see how difficult that would be, there is an obvious risk of the Pod breaking before it reaches the washer. If you have a laundry room in your home and can keep your detergent within easy reach--no problem. The plastic bag the Pods come in is sturdy enough to keep them safe. But if, like me, you share a washer with others, or go to the local laundromat, it's not going to really be much more convenient than carrying a container of detergent to carry the whole bag.  My biggest concern is for parents. Having two young children myself, I am always aware of potential hazards and things that need to be kept out of reach. Obviously, laundry detergent always should be out of little one's hands. But the Pods themselves look like some kind of colorful candy or toy. The colorful swirls of stainlifter and fabric softener on the on side may look snazzy for packaging, but they also make these look appealing to kiddies. I'm not saying parents will necessarily let them fall into the hands of children, but it's still a danger.  In conclusion, these are good if convenience is your goal and you can store these close to your washer to use. But I'll stick to regular detergent so I can vary the amount I use.  Happy Washing! AUTHOR: SALLY ADDINGTON
TITLE: Love these pods

content_cleaned:
I'm one of those people who ends up using more detergent when I have to measure. I know I shouldn't, and that it's probably not good for the machine to put in too much but I kind of go by the saying, "If a little bit is good, a lot is better!" So these little pods take all the guessing and over-estimating out of getting the detergent into the machine to do a load of wash.

I'm very picky about fragrances in laundry detergents so while these pods looked like a good way to simplify measuring laundry detergent, I was a little skeptical about the fragrance part. I've tried the Mystic Forest and the Ocean Mist so far and I like the smell of both, but neither is overwhelming. The Mystic Forest has kind of a woodsy scent mixed with a little floral. The Ocean Mist has an outdoorsy, clean fragrance. I generally look for unscented detergents but these are light and they kind of go away after a while rather than hanging around to compete with your cologne.

I've used these on a load of colored clothing, a load of whites and a load of dog blankets and fleece furniture throws. It got the "doggy" smell out of the fleece dog blankets and got them clean. Anything that can eliminate the dog smell, especially this time of year when they're in and out of the rain is good in my book. I've always had good luck with the cleaning abilities of Tide and consider it one of the best detergents out there.

I purchased small packages of these pods at a local store to try them. They're very expensive that way if you figure out the cost per washload. The best deal is the 77 pod size and this is the size I sent as a gift to my aunt who seems to always be doing laundry when I visit. That's also the size I'll be ordering for myself from now on. (BTW, Amazon's price on the large size is the same as Wal-Mart per pod since their large size is only 72 pods.) They're still expensive if you compare the cost to a bulk container of Tide liquid detergent, but I usually end up using more detergent than I need (Don't ask me why, I think it must be some kind of "over measuring because I think my clothes won't get clean" character defect.) so using these cute little pre-measured pods will possibly save me money in the long run.

One thing to remember is to make sure your hands are dry when grabbing a new pod from the container. These are meant to dissolve very easily in both hot and cold water (I used them in warm/cold) so you could end up with a mucky mess if water from your hands gets into the container. I made that mistake with some dishwashing pods and had a hard time separating the stuck together pods the next time I went into the container.

Two thumbs up for an easy to use product that gets my clothes clean and fresh smelling.

AUTHOR: ColePep
TITLE: Awesome Concept

content_cleaned: I've used it on three loads of laundry, which I tried to vary in order to provide a proper test. I am using a large-capacity top-loader, and my usual detergent of choice, although I shop sales and coupons as well, has been liquid Wisk, because I find it superior for pre-treating. I generally use a hot wash and a cold rinse. These are packets of detergent and additives--very cute, BTW--that you toss in the washer and let do their thing. The instructions say that one packet is enough for most loads. First I tried it with a medium-sized load of mixed laundry, and it did very well indeed. Things were clean and bright. Then I tried it with a larger, but not very large, load of clothing only, and there I saw a small problem. My husband (works from home) gets up in the morning and puts on a pair of white socks; he puts on shoes only if he is going outside. By the end of the day, those socks can be distressingly grubby on the bottom (Why, no, I don't mop the floor every day--why do you ask?). The socks did not get as clean as they usually do with the Wisk, and the undershirts also seemed less bright than usual. It would do; I'm not obsessive about the laundry--if it's been washed, I'm not going to wash it again--but it didn't look as clean. Perhaps I should have tried two packets, but it did say that most loads only need one, and it wasn't an unusual load. Finally, I did a quite large load of sheets and towels, and they were fine, although sheets and towels usually are. The one thing that would take time to figure out is the cost. By tedious comparison, I found that I spent less money on _dishwasher_ detergent using the packets, because I was wasting less, even though the packets have a higher unit price than the boxes. But that calculation required--well, you know what it required, with the counting and the measuring and the cost-per-load. To sum up, I really liked the convenience of the packets. I wasn't overly impressed with how clean they got things, but those socks are a special case, and it did well enough on most things. I might use them again if the price turns out to be an advantage, but I'll still have to keep something else on hand for pre-treating, since the package specifies that the packets cannot be broken or used for pre-treating.

AUTHOR: Walter F. Lee "(Bargain Affectionado)"
TITLE: Works but at what cost?

content_cleaned: Dishwasher pods work great. I wish I could say the same about laundry pods. Tide is my favorite brand. I use many Tide products for different laundry needs. The concept of detergent, stain remover and brightener all rolled into one Tide pod seemed like a good idea until I actually tried them.  Today's washers (including top-loaders) must comply with stringent government standards to be more water and energy efficient. That means a warm wash temperature is more like a cold wash, and there's not much you can do about it. I have a brand new washing machine, and Tide pods don't readily dissolve in warm temperature mode. Old-fashioned and reliable powders (or liquids) quickly dissipate in any water temp. The pods don't dissolve until the machine starts to agitate. That wastes time before adding clothes, somewhat defeating the purpose of pods.  If there is a noticeable difference because of an added stain remover and brightener in the pod, I certainly can't detect it. Yet, I do see results when using individual stain removing or brightening products when needed. I don't always need a stain remover or brightener...this pod is sounding less and less attractive.  One pod supposedly handles all loads, regardless of size. Tide suggests using two pods for very dirty clothes. I used one pod with a small laundry load. It sure made a lot of suds! There's something to be said about user control.  The pods smell great, but clothes don't smell anything like that after drying. I've learned an expensive lesson here. Tide products work best when not in pod form.

TITLE: Very Good Detergent!!

content_cleaned: I am used to buying Dropps Laundry Detergent Pacs, Scent + Dye Free, 80-Load Pouch, 31.1 Ounce Pouch for my daughter. It is nice to have her detergent in a little pouch and drop it in and be ready. I also bought some Dropps that were not for sensitive skin but for some reason, the pouches did not dissolve.  The real selling factor was these are both for top lop and front load. I own a HE front load washer. I decided to test the pods with two same sleep shirts I own. One I accidently washed with something red in warm water. The sleep shirts were both gray originally but one had a pink tint I could not get out. I decided to throw them in with a full load of medium colors on cold water. I was amazed when the shirts came out! The shirt that had the pink tint to it was almost gone! It was very hard to tell them apart.  My next test was I spilled some food on my shirt while eating. It was cheese and greasy. I did not notice it right away but did when I was getting the clothes ready to wash at night. I usually use a deep stain remover and let the garment sit for ten or so minutes, then throw everything in the wash; most of the time the clothes come out stain free. However, this time I did not pre-treat but only used a pod. I was nervous that the stain was still going to be in the shirt. When I took it out of the washer it appeared to be gone but it is hard to tell if grease is really gone until you dry the garment. I dried it and the shirt had no stains on it!  I do think these are expensive but when you factor in the money you will save from not having to buy as much, or even needing separate stain remover, it might be worth it. Also, you have to wait for the other stuff to sit so if you do not have time on your side, this might be worth it for you too.  I am impressed but think some stains will still require the stain remover, just not as much or even any depending on the type. I have never been a big fan of Tide but am very impressed.  March 21, 2012: My mother came over today as I was making the bed. I had just washed the linens with the Spring Meadow pods. She walked in and said how great the room smelled. I felt like I was in a commercial, I told her to smell the linens, she said that was it. She was very impressed at the smell.  I wanted to add that even though these are for front load HE washers, it is still hard to tell my brain to place the pod in the drum and not in the pull out tray. That is what the instructions state. I almost placed it in the tray today and had to remind myself to place it in the drum. These are the only ones I do that with though.

content_cleaned: Laundry detergent is not an exciting product, but improvements like this are welcome. AUTHOR: Menthol Rum
TITLE: A nice improvement in laundry detergent

content_cleaned: The Tide pods are convenient, they clean well in hot or cold water and the laundry smells good. Using 1 pod for a regular load or 2 for a larger/heavily soiled load with my top loading washer, I didn't notice the laundry (whites or colors) to be any brighter or more stain-free than with my regular liquid laundry detergent. So 2 of the 3 selling points weren't evident to me. These are great for space-conscious college kids to store and use, for those unwilling to lug the jugs of detergent OR for travel laundry as long as they're in a plastic travel soap dish in checked luggage. I do loads of laundry while on the road so the pods are a welcome convenience to a point. Otherwise, 40 regular laundry loads using pods at the sale price of $11.27 costs me about a nickle more a load for the convenience. BUT at the regular price of $21.27 that's $.53 a regular 1 pod load it's NOT worth it to me. They are just OK, nothing out of the ordinary other than their convenience. ***KEEP OUT OF REACH OF KIDS, the pretty colored pods are attractive but ingestion requires a call to poison control. PS I am hoping the packets actually did fully dissolve and are not hiding somewhere to jam up my washer.

First, to all the people complaining about them sticking together, they need to be kept in a cool place. Otherwise they will melt and stick together as a lot of people seem to be complaining about.

Back to what I stated above, she keeps them in my nephew's bedroom, who like to keep it cold in there, and hasn't encountered a single pod that was stuck to another or melted, nor has she had any that didn't dissolve in the wash, so I'm not sure why other users are having the issue. Possibly over loading the washer?
Anyway, I used up the 6 my mother gave me (ocean mist scent) and I absolutely LOVE these little guys. We used to use liquid detergent in my house and it always went too fast as everyone seems to use more detergent than necessary. With the pods it's simple; drop in one pod per load and you're good! Clothes come out clean, soft and they smell great.
Highly recommended.
